fields.name: Build a Mighty Machine
fields.description: Build a mighty machine that jumps up, sideways, or flips over. The whole structure should jump into the air.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, these are just a few ways to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!


  1. Find different ways to attach your rigid objects and rubber bands together. Winding or stretching a rubber band can be a great way to store elastic energy!
  2. See if you can create a latch system for your design, so that it releases its elastic energy when the latch is released (similarly to how an umbrella latch is used to release open an umbrella, and how the mantis shrimp kept its are cocked and ready to punch!).
  3. Test your design, and see how far it can jump!
  4. Once you have a jumping machine, find a way to make the machine jump using only 1 finger. Here are a few ideas:
    • Think of how latches on umbrellas work to hold them open. How does the latch keep potential energy from being released until the latch is pushed?
    • Think of how the button on a tape measure can keep it from winding up and also allow the tape to snap back into its holder.
fields.learn_more:
Scientist Sheila Patek found that the fastest animals in the world rely on a quick release of energy in order to propel themselves or deliver an extremely fast, powerful punch! When a trapjaw ant opens its large jaws and pushed them against the ground, it is building elastic potential energy, or energy that is building due to something being stretched or compressed from its natural shape. In this case, the energy is the result of the tendons in the ant’s jaws being stretched like a rubber band! When the trapjaw ant allows its jaws to snap shut (and release all the energy very quickly), it causes the ant to fly several body lengths away!

In this design challenge, you are going to build your own Mighty Machine that can store potential energy in the rubber bands. This machine will be able to jump when you release it which is when the stored potential energy is converted (changed) to kinetic energy. Kinetic energy is the energy used to make something move. Lets get building!

fields.name: Construct a Crane
fields.description: Build a crane that uses simple machines and mechanical advantage to move heavy objects.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, these are just a few ways to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!


  1. Start building the base of your crane. It should be tall and stable enough to hold the weight of the object you want to carry.
  2. Make the arm of the crane. This will be the lever of your crane that can move freely up and down, as well as side to side, like your own arm.
  3. Think about what materials to use and how you will connect the base and the arm together so that parts can move around easily. Hint: Try wrapping a pipe cleaner around a dowel that has washers on it!
  4. Build your pulley(s) to help you pick things up with the crane. A pulley is just a wheel with a string wrapped around it. Make sure the wheel can easily rotate.
  5. Think about where you want your string to go to help you lift objects with the crane. Make sure it goes along the arm and down the base without tangling or falling off. Hint: Taping sections of a straw to the arm and the base can help guide the string along your crane.
  6. Design how you will carry your load. It can be a scoop, a series of ropes, or a hook. Make sure you attach it to the string so it can pick things up.
  7. Now you are ready to test your crane! Try picking up and moving objects around.
  8. Once you master a crane with one pulley, try building one with two so it can lift even more weight! The more pulleys you use, the easier it is to lift something up.
fields.learn_more:
Cranes are large machines that can help us lift and move very heavy objects using mechanical advantage. They are made with a combination of simple machines like pulleys, levers, and wheels to move heavy things from one place to another. These simple machines help the crane use mechanical advantage to get jobs done more easily.

Mechanical advantage allows us to do work with less effort. For example, a pulley is a wheel with a rope wrapped around it that is used to make lifting something heavy easier. One pulley can change the direction of the force. Multiple pulleys can change the direction of the force and spread weight of the load, making it even easier to move something! A lever is a simple machine made out of a rigid bar fixed on a hinge or fulcrum. This machine provides leverage, which is another word for mechanical advantage. Have you ever played on a see-saw or used scissors? Both of these are great examples of levers.

Cranes are often attached to a heavy base to act as a counterweight that the crane does not tip over when it lifts objects. You will need to think about how the weight is distributed and balanced when building a structure like a crane. In your design you want to think about where to place this counterweight so the crane does not tip over when lifting heavy objects.

In this design challenge, you are going to build a crane that uses simple machines and mechanical advantage to move heavy objects. Your crane must be able to lift off a cup off the table and move it somewhere else. .

fields.name: Engineer an Air-Powered Spinning Machine
fields.description: Build an air-powered spinning machine inspired by Boeing CST-100 Starliner.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, these are just a few ways to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!


    Version 1
  1. Carefully use a sharpened pencils to make two small holes in a ping pong ball. These should be directly across from each other. Push a long skewer or other material through these holes to form the air-powered spinning machine axis, or line around which the sphere will rotate. The ball should spin freely.
  2. With a pencil or pen, mark the equator, or middle, of your ping pong ball. This line should be perpendicular to the axis.
  3. Make holes along the equator where you will insert vents. You can make as few or as many as you think will be necessary to spin the ping pong ball.
  4. Insert straws to these new holes to form vents. Cut them so there’s an inch or two of straight straw on either side of the flexible part.
  5. Cut a circle out of cardboard and poke the axis through it so your ping pong ball will sit on top of it while you hold it.
  6. Take a straw and place it over the skewer or pencil (above the circle) and with a deep breath blow into the straw.

    Version 2:
  1. Make a hole in the bottom of a paper cup. Place the cup upside-down and insert a long, straight stick in the hole.
  2. Secure the cup on a table. Slide a piece of a straw over the stick.
  3. Tape a straw or stick on top of the piece of straw to form a "T".
  4. Blow up two balloons and use paperclips to keep them from losing air.
  5. Tape the balloons to opposite sides of the "T". Make sure they face in opposite directions and don't wiggle too much.
  6. Carefully take off the paper clips and let the balloons go at the same time. Your machine should spin!
fields.learn_more:
Thousands of years ago, an ancient Greek named “Hero” wrote notes about an experiment where he boiled water using a special pot. He called it an aeolipile. Water heated in a cauldron would produce steam, which would then rise into a sphere. The steam would collect in the sphere, building pressure until forced to exit through bent vents with great force. The force of the exiting steam created a thrust, or strong push, in the opposite direction that the steam exits from, and caused the sphere to spin. This is Newton’s third law of motion where it says “For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.”

Today, Tony Castilleja and other engineers use the same idea when they make spaceships! In order for a vehicle to steer itself in space, it uses the same principle of thrust. The CST-100 Starliner has 24 onboard thrusters, which push gases out a nozzle to make the ship move in the opposite direction. It uses the thrusters to navigate through space, slow down, and dock at the International Space Station. Each thruster works just like vents on an aeolipile! Imagine releasing air from a balloon. If the opening faces to the right, which direction does the balloon move in?

In this design challenge, you are going to build your own air-powered spinning machine inspired by the thrusters on the CST-100 Starliner!

To learn more about what Tony works on and how the CST 100 works, check this out!

As part of Boeing's centennial, Boeing engineers teamed up with several leading educational partners to co-create K-12 educational resources that celebrate the science behind the past 100 years of aerospace advancement and ready students, teachers, and families with skills for the next century. Learn more about it here.

fields.name: Build a “No Wire” Circuit
fields.description: Create a circuit that has no metal wires and uses at least three different conductors.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Decide on how you want to create your circuit and pick at least three different conductive materials you want to use
  2. Lay your materials out on a piece of cardboard and secure them together using tape. Make sure that the conductive pieces are touching!
  3. After you have created a pathway to your battery from your LED, create a switch to close your circuit and turn on your LED. You can also try to Engineer an Electric Switch if you need help figuring this part out!
  4. Helpful Hints:
  5. If you are using pipe cleaners make sure to pull out some fuzz to make them conduct better! You only need to pull out fuzz where they will be touching other conductors in your circuit.
  6. Make sure you are connecting the + positive side of the LED (long leg) to the + positive side of the battery.
  7. If your circuit isn’t working, look for a break in the connections. The materials have to be connected well for the electricity to flow through your circuit.
fields.learn_more:
Electricity is the flow of electrons from one place to another. We are able to utilize electricity by creating a circuit. A circuit is a loop in which electrical current is able to flow from a power source like a battery through an object your trying to power, like an LED, and back to the battery. Circuits need to have a power source, like the battery pack, a load, like the LED, and a way to let the electricity flow. Conductors, are what enable the electricity to flow through a circuit

Everything conducts electricity but some materials are much better than others. Conductors are materials that allow electricity to easily pass through them. Metal are good conductors. Copper is one of the best conductors of electricity and most wires are made of copper. Insulators are materials l that make it hard for electricity to pass through them. Plastics are some of the best insulators.

In this design challenge you are going to explore conductive materials by building a circuit to light an LED without the help of wires. Try various materials that you might find around your house to build your circuit. Remember that almost all metals are great conductors so find objects that are made up of at least some metal and see if they conduct some electricity. The more materials that you use to build your circuit the more you’ll learn about what does and does not conduct electricity.

To be safe use a battery that does not have very much power, like a 3 volt watch battery. If you use more than 5V in your circuit you could burn out your LED!

fields.learn_more:
In the video, Dr. Paul Ekman talks about how some facial expressions are universally understood. Emotions like happiness, sadness, surprise, and anger can be understood across cultures by people who speak different languages through their facial expressions!

By closely looking at the mechanical systems in the face, or how muscles work to cause movement of other facial parts, each expression can be broken into a series of movements. These movements are controlled by many individual muscles working together to form one expression. This is just like a series of mechanisms working together create one larger system or machine!

In this design challenge, you are going to build a robotic face that can make one or more expression in a mechanical way. Design moving facial features that express how your robot is feeling!

Get creative in your design. Think about the way the face is moving during each expression. It might be helpful to ask a friend to make the face you are trying to recreate and draw it using arrows to indicate the direction each muscle is moving!

fields.name: Engineer a Bird Beak
fields.description: Engineer a beak that will allow you to pick up as much food as possible in one try without using your hands.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Connect your pencils together with rubber bands to create a system that closes when you apply effort with your hands. Feel free to use a variety of long, rigid objects.
  2. Think of the connection areas of your long, rigid objects as fulcrums--what materials and structure will allow for the easiest movement of the pencils?

fields.learn_more:
As David Bonter explained in the video, before making long flights over bodies of water, birds have to “fuel up” to be sure they have enough energy to make the flight. The design and effectiveness of a bird’s beak has a huge impact on their success as a species. Birds who are able to eat more food with less effort will be able to migrate more easily when harsh weather arrives.

Some birds are able to eat hard foods, like nuts, which offer a high amount of calories (aka fuel). This is because their beaks use mechanical advantage to break through the nut’s shell easily. Mechanical advantage gives birds the ability to amplify the force of their beaks. Though beaks vary in size and shape, the overall structures of beaks are similar. Most bird beaks allow for a large load (or food in this case) to be consumed because the fulcrum, or area of the beak that permits movement, is very sensitive to effort, or the amount of energy, that it takes to move the beak.

Because beaks have this special combination of fulcrums, parts sensitive to effort and the ability to accommodate a large load they are able to crack open hard nuts and seeds!

fields.name: Build a Self-Powered Rocket
fields.description: Use a simple chemical reaction to launch a small object.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Note: Do this design challenge outside, and wear protective safety glasses. Once you do step 2, you have about 15 seconds before your chemical reaction causes a launch, so work quickly and run through the steps a few times before using water.
  2. Fill you film canister ½ to ⅔ full with water, and add ½ for a crushed alka seltzer tablet to the canister. This will be the reaction chamber of your rocket!
  3. Quickly put the lid on the canister. Place the canister on the ground and back away quickly.
  4. Repeat your launch, and place your marble or gumball on top of the canister before snapping it shut. The gumball or marble is your space shuttle. CAREFUL: the marble will shoot upwards at great velocity, step away from the canister as soon as the marble is in place, and NEVER put your face over the rocket.
fields.learn_more:
Have you ever watched a rocket launch a shuttle into space? Did you wonder how a launch works, and why the rocket is able to move at such high speeds?

You might be surprised to learn that rocket launches are the result of the movements of tiny molecules! Molecules are atoms bonded together – such as water (which is made of 3 atoms: 2 hydrogen and 1 oxygen).

When a rocket launches, it combines hydrogen (H2) and oxygen (O2) molecules and heats them – resulting in a chemical reaction, recombining the hydrogen and oxygen atoms into water molecules. This chemical reaction produces heat and steam, which moves quickly and is forced out of the rocket’s thrusters, pushing the rocket upward! Thrust is the force that pushes something rapidly in a direction.

In this design challenge, you’ll create your own launcher powered by a chemical reaction and create a large thrust! Wear safety goggles, and do this design challenge outside.

Interesting fact: Alka seltzer is powdered acetic acid (vinegar) and sodium bicarbonate (baking soda). When an alka seltzer tablet is placed in water, the water helps to free the vinegar and baking soda molecules so they can react with each other, creating a fizz of carbon dioxide bubbles – the water isn't actually part of the chemical reaction!

fields.name: Build a Stomp Rocket
fields.description: Design a stomp rocket propelled by air pressure that can fly at least 10 ft in the air.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Using a pvc pipe or straw, build your rocket by wrapping a piece of construction paper around a pipe. Make sure the paper cylinder wrapped tight, but that the pipe can still move freely.
  2. When the paper is taped, remove the PVC pipe from within the paper cylinder and cap the top end using tape.
  3. Build a nose cone and attach fins to the rocket to help it cut through the air and fly farther.
  4. Use your PVC pipe or straw to create a tube with a 45 degree bend near one end.
  5. Attach your water bottle or bulb syringe to one end of the pipe.
  6. Slip your rocket over the pipe opening and stomp on the water bottle or bulb and watch your rocket fly!
fields.learn_more:
When NASA scientists get ready to launch a rocket, they have to be sure that the rocket will be able overcome the force of gravity. This is difficult, because gravity pulls objects toward the ground (this is why you always land after jumping up!), making it very difficult for anything to leave Earth’s atmosphere. In the video, Raul was able to send a toy shuttle into space using a helium balloon, making it weigh less than air and rise, very similarly to how bubbles rise to the top of a glass of soda. The toy shuttle and balloon fell back to Earth when enough helium leaked out of the balloon to make it heavier than air again.

In your design challenge, you are going to launch a rocket by creating a thrust, or strong push, that causes your object to move upward against the force of gravity. In your stomp rocket design, you will use an air bladder to hold a large amount of air, which can be squeezed (or stomped on!) to force the air out very quickly. If you direct all this escaping air into your rocket, it will thrust the rocket forward!

In order to travel at very high speeds along a predictable path, rockets need to have an aerodynamic shape that will allow them to cut through the air easily, reducing air resistance. Air resistance is the reason objects moving through air slow down – to move forward, an object has to push through millions of invisible air molecules, which slow it down and reduce its forward thrust. Objects with pointed fronts, like airplanes and arrows, are able to shove air molecules aside, which allows them to move forward more easily.

fields.name: Build a Suspension Bridge
fields.description: Build a suspension bridge that spans 10 inches and can hold at least 15 pennies!
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Set up your bridge site! Place two desks or chairs about 10 inches apart. Your bridge will span the space between.
  2. Poke the ends of the paper clip into opposite sides of a paper cup near the rim to make a load tester. Use a second paper clip to make a hook to hang the load tester from the bridge.
  3. Construct your bridge, and place it so that it spans the gap between the two desks or chairs. Use the load tester to see how much weight it can hold.
  4. Add some trusses to your bridge, and see how much more weight it can hold.
  5. Now turn your truss bridge into a suspension bridge to make it even stronger! Build towers for the bridge to suspend from, as well as cables to connect the floor of the bridge to the towers. See how much more weight your suspension bridge can hold.
fields.learn_more:
Sofia Puerto, a civil engineer, teaches us why suspension bridges are able to be so long and so strong! As a civil engineer, Sofia uses her expertise in science and engineering to build amazing bridges that can span very wide distances. In this challenge, you are going to build a bridge that can withstand weight and add trusses and suspension to your design so that it can hold up more weight just like Sofia’s bridges!

As engineers, we look to some of nature’s smallest creatures for inspiration. Spider webs are extremely good at withstanding tension, or being stretched. In addition to building a web with strong and flexible spider silk, the spider starts building with a Y-shaped structure that provides the core support for the web and helps to tolerate extreme tension (like suspension cables on a bridge). The spider then incorporates triangular shapes, criss-crosses, and spiral structures to strengthen the web (like trusses that structural engineers use in bridges and skyscrapers). Engineers use these same types of structures to strengthen bridges that support the weight of cars and people.

fields.name: Engineer a Landing Device
fields.description: Build a device that will slow down your payload as it falls so it lands gently when dropped from 8 feet high.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, these are just a few ways to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!

    Version 1:
  1. Build your payload, a Mars Rover! Alternatively, you can use a small, somewhat heavy object such as a toy car for your payload.
  2. Construct a carrier for your payload that will help it stay upright as it falls.
  3. Build an attachment to your carrier that creates enough drag to slow your rover when it is being dropped from an 8 foot height. The heavier your payload, the more drag your carrier will need to create!
    Version 2:
  1. Find or make a lightweight box can hold your payload.
  2. Tape together sheets of lightweight paper to create a large, flat shape. This will create a large surface area for the landing device.
  3. Use tape to attach the box to the large, flat paper shape.
  4. Use pipe cleaners to create hooks or arches that attach to the top of the box.
  5. Create a parachute from tissue paper or thin plastic. Attach the parachute to the pipe cleaners, and test your design!
fields.learn_more:
In the video, Scientist Eric Blood talks about the special parachute built to land the Curiosity Rover on Mars. The parachute is able to create drag, which helps land the rover safely onto the surface of Mars. Drag is impacted by the velocity or speed of the object falling, air density (how many air molecules there are in a volume or air, such as the atmosphere of Mars), and the shape of the landing device. Mars has a very low air density (very few air molecules compared to the earth’s atmosphere), and less friction from air molecules to slow the rover’s fall. It is very important that we design a landing device that is able to create as much drag as possible, catching as many air molecules as it can in order to slow the fall.

For the Curiosity Rover, a special parachute was designed specifically for the rover so that it can land safely on Mars. In this challenge, you are going to build a landing device for a payload. You want to make sure the payload can land right-side-up and safely from a great height, as there won’t be anyone on Mars to help repair or flip it over!

Check out this video from Science Friday with more Curiosity Rover inspiration!
fields.mentor_guide:
Challenge: Build a device that will slow down as it falls, to minimize force of impact when dropped from 8 feet high.

Top Mentor Feedback Example!

Jessica mentoring Sophia's project: https://www.curiositymachine.org/challenges/13/Baymax8/build/

Concepts: Students will explore the concepts of aerodynamic forces and impact.

Speed

How far an object has travelled over a total period of time (distance).

Velocity

How much an object has moved in relation to the initial starting point, over the amount of time taken (displacement).

Distance vs. Displacement

Distance is the length of how much an object has traveled during its journey, while displacement is the distance in relation to the object’s starting point.

Drag

A type of friction that slows down the movement of an object travelling through air. It is dependent on the surface area of the object in contact with air. Also known as air resistance.

Impact or Collision

The forces that occur when two or more objects collide, which depends on speed, acceleration, material, and surface area of object.

Air Density

The amount of air or fluid molecules that are in the atmosphere to help create drag, which slows down a falling object.



Feedback Advice:

The students may have not created enough surface area to provide drag.

  • “What would happen if you increased or decreased the surface area of the parachute part of your landing device?”

The force of impact or collision may make the lander unstable or break.

  • “Can you try adding stuff to the bottom of the lander to absorb the force when it hits the ground?”

fields.name: Engineer an Electric Switch
fields.description: Build a switch that can complete a circuit to turn on an LED.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Before building your switch and circuit, make sure your hands are dry or wear protective rubber gloves. Sweat is a great conductor of electricity, and can allow the electrical current to shock you!
  2. Attach the battery to an LED (light emitting diode) with wires. Your LED will only light up when electricity flows through it in the right direction. You may have to reverse the direction of the LED attachment to the battery to ensure that the LED lights up.
  3. Test out different materials you find around the house to see what is insulative and what is conductive. Try things like paper clips, straws, chalk, wooden stick, nails, foil, rubber bands etc.
  4. Build a switch with a combination of insulative and conductive materials. Your switch needs to be able to open and close a gap in your circuit in order to turn the LED on and off.
  5. Make sure your switch can be operated safely by someone who has sweaty hands! Add insulative material to your switch “toggle” so that it is safer to use.
fields.learn_more:
Engineer Burcin Becerik-Gerber wants to change the way that people interact with their homes by developing a way for a home to automatically change its temperature and lighting to suit a person’s preferences. Since these systems rely on electricity to function, the very first step in achieving Burcin’s goal is to find a way to easily stop and start the flow of electricity.

Electricity travels through a circuit only when it is a complete loop, ending where it started from, at the electrical source (such as a battery). The wires and other components of an electrical circuit create a pathway for the flow of electricity to follow, much like a water flows through tubes.

If you want to control when electricity can flow through a circuit, you can include a switch that can open (turn off) and close (turn on) the circuit. Switches can be made of a combination of materials of insulators and conductors. Insulative materials which don’t allow electricity to easily flow through them (such as wood, rubber, or cardboard) can be used to hold the wiring and other conductive components of your circuit in place. Conductive materials allow electricity to flow easily through them (such as copper and aluminum), and can be used to bridge the switch’s gap in your circuit.

fields.name: Learn to Draw Proportions
fields.description: Draw an animal with accurate proportions.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Find an animal you want to draw. This could be a figurine, photograph, or even an animal on display at a museum! This will be your “subject”.
  2. Start by drawing the animal as large simple shapes. For example, use your pencil to measure the height and width of your subject's head and draw an oval with the same proportions. Hint: If your subject is really big, try standing far enough away from it that you can see its whole body without moving your head. You can measure the animal's proportions by holding a pencil or string an arm's length from your body. The measurements you take from this distance should be small enough to fit on your drawing paper.
  3. Continue measuring and drawing the rest of your subject's body.
  4. Once you've drawn the whole subject, double-check its proportions by measuring the subject's entire width and height. Does it match what you've drawn?
  5. Once you've finished drawing your subject's body proportions, you can start adding details like eyes, feathers, fur, and scales!
fields.learn_more:
Have you ever tried to draw your pet, family, or favorite superhero? It can be very difficult to make your drawing look like the person or animal you are trying to draw. Now, imagine if you had to draw something that you had never seen before. How would you know what it looked like?

Scientific illustrators like Stephanie Abramowicz make illustrations of animals that went extinct millions of years ago, and that people have never seen before! She works with paleontologists to piece together clues on what these animals might have looked like from fossilized bones and observations of modern animals like birds and reptiles. One of the most important things for Stephanie to understand when drawing these animals is their proportions.

Proportions are how the size of one part of an animal compares to its whole body. For example, T. rex is known for its large head and feet – these parts are larger than those of other animals when compared to the rest of its body. To understand the proportions of an animal, you must be able to simplify the information you see into simple shapes and concentrate on the size of the shape in relation to the rest of the object you are drawing.

fields.name: Make a Stable Boat
fields.description: Build a boat that can hold as many pennies as possible.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Build the main structure of your boat using the wire screen or other material that you think will create a boat that holds weight.
  2. Wrap the structure of your boat with a material that you think will waterproof it.
  3. Fill your water testing station up and test your boat by adding weight.
  4. If your boat starts to sink, note how you can redesign it to hold more weight.
fields.learn_more:
Have you ever been on a boat? Did you notice that you were able to stand up and walk around? This is because the boat was stable, even though the water keeping it afloat may have been moving a lot. In this video, Naval Engineer Carolyn Judge explains how its possible to build a boat that is both fast and stable in the water.

A boat is designed to be stable in order to hold people, machines, and cargo comfortably. In order for a boat to stay afloat, the buoyancy, or upward force pushing from the water, must be greater than gravity, or the downward force pulling the boat closer to the earth. For the boat to remain stable, the center of buoyancy and the center of gravity must line up.

The shape and weight of a boat design helps make it more or less buoyant. If a boat has too much weight and a small surface area, it will sink and won’t be very stable. If the shape is too narrow, then the boat can tip over easily. Engineers deal with the balance of all these things to make a good design for a boat to hold large amounts of weight and float at the same time.

fields.name: Build a Submarine
fields.description: Build a submarine that will dive down through the water and come back to the surface.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Attach the balloon to each end of the tubing using rubber bands.
  2. Cut your tubing in half so that you now have two short pieces of tubing, each attached to a balloon.
  3. Fill your syringes with air, and then attach them to the newly cut ends of the tubes.
  4. Make two holes on the empty bottle and feed the balloon ends through the holes. Be sure that the balloons won’t fall out once you secure them!
  5. Add weights to the bottle and place it under the water. Make sure the syringe does not fall into the water and try to remove as much as as possible from the bottle.
  6. Once you have the submarine sunk to the bottom of the tub. Use the syringe to blow up the balloon to get the submarine to rise.
fields.learn_more:
Submarines are special ships that can go completely under the water’s surface and then come back up again—a trick that other ships usually can’t do!

A real submarine has different compartments that control how it will sink or rise to different heights of the ocean. It has metal tanks called ballast tanks that hold different amounts of air and water depending on if you want to submarine to rise higher or sink lower. The submarine can pump water and air into and out of the ballast tanks to make it heavier or lighter and help it move up and down in the water!

Imagine what will happen to your submarine if all the ballast tanks are filled with air only. I bet you can guess! It will rise towards the surface of the water. Why? Because water is more dense and heavier than air, a submarine filled with air will float above the heavier water surrounding it. By introducing more air, you are making your submarine more buoyant which causes it to float opposite to have gravity causes objects to sink.

In the video Professor Dario Pompili, talked about using robot vehicles that submerge and move underwater to explore the vast ocean. In this design challenge, we are going to build a submarine that can sink and rise just like how a real submarine does. You are going to be designing your own ballast tanks using balloons. Adding weights to change the buoyancy of your submarine.

fields.name: Build a Wind Powered Sailboat
fields.description: Build a sailboat that is powered by the wind.
fields.how_to_make_it:
Remember, this is only one way to do this design, see if you can do it a different way!



  1. Create a boat using aluminum or other materials. Make sure it is waterproof.
  2. Design a sail that can catch a lot of wind.
  3. Attach your sail to the boat.
  4. Place your sailboat in the water and turn on the fan.
  5. Test your sailboat. See if it tips over or takes on water--how can you improve it?
fields.learn_more:
In the video, Carolyn Judge talks about how making a fast boat presents many difficulties. The boat’s Center of Gravity and Center of Buoyancy have to be balanced in order for the boat to stay right-side-up and above water! Be a naval engineer and design a fast wind powered boat that stays afloat without tipping over!

In this design challenge you are going to harness wind energy (from the fan) to make your sailboat move fast. When designing your sail, think about how big and what shape your it should be. You want the sail to have a large surface area to catch as much wind as possible without tipping over the boat. Think about when you stick your hand out of a moving car, and how when you change the angle of your palm your hand is pushed by the wind in different ways.

As Carolyn Judge mentions, when designing a boat, a boat engineer needs to account for the added force to the boat, and where it is applied. This is referred to as the Center of Lift which is the point on your boat on which the force (wind) is applied. After attaching a sail to your boat, you may need to adjust the boat’s Center of Gravity to keep the boat from tipping at high speeds. Center of gravity is the point where the object’s weight is concentrated.

Think about how to balance these as you design your speedy sailboat!

fields.name: Kindergarten-2nd Grade Engineering Design Process
fields.description: Inspire young students to make observations and find solutions to problems.
fields.overview:
Inspire your students to be curious, creative, and persistent learners! With these project-based lessons, provide an engaging learning experience for students while also meeting all NGSS in Engineering Design standards for the Kindergarten-2nd grade levels.

You can pair the lessons and student worksheets here with any Curiosity Machine design challenge. To help you out, we've featured some design challenges that are great for young children below. Our Kindergarten-2nd Engineering Design materials can be used as-is (just use the pdf files we've linked) or customized for your own classroom (download the .docx files and Curiosity Machine icon font and edit away)!

    Activity 1 Questions and Observations

  • Lesson Plan, Lesson Plan (editable)
  • Worksheet, Worksheet (editable)

    Activity 2 Shapes and Problem Solving

  • Lesson Plan, Lesson Plan (editable)
  • Worksheet, Worksheet (editable)

    Activity 3 Test and Compare

  • Lesson Plan, Lesson Plan (editable)
  • Worksheet, Worksheet (editable)

    Curiosity Machine Font (optional, if you'd like to edit the materials)

  • Font Icon and Installation Guide
  • Font file

Through Curiosity Machine, students will also benefit from individual mentorship on their work from scientists and engineers. To provide the best experience for your students, please watch the Curiosity Machine Introduction video and consider a Curiosity Machine membership if you haven't already.
